\text{This paper proposes the Diffusion Model-Based Predictor (DMBP) for state-denoising in offline reinforcement learning (RL) tasks. DMBP leverages conditional diffusion models to recover the actual state for decision-making. To mitigate the error accumulation in state estimation, a non-Markovian training objective is proposed. The proposed framework can effectively deal with the cases of incomplete state observations for state-based RL tasks.}

$$\text{Strengths:}
\text{1. The proposed framework leverages conditional diffusion models to recover the actual state for decision-making, which can effectively mitigate the error accumulation in state estimation.}
\text{2. The non-Markovian training objective can reduce the error accumulation in the test phase.}
\text{3. The proposed framework can effectively deal with the cases of incomplete state observations for state-based RL tasks.}
\text{4. The experiments demonstrate the robustness of the proposed framework against different scales of random noises and even adversarial attacks.}

$$\text{Weaknesses:}
\text{1. The proposed framework may require significant computational resources due to the parallel denoising process in the diffusion model.}
\text{2. The non-Markovian training objective may require a large number of samples for training, which can be challenging in practice.}
\text{3. The experiments may not cover all the possible cases of incomplete state observations for state-based RL tasks.}
\text{4. The robustness of the proposed framework against adversarial attacks may require further evaluation.}

$$\text{Suggestions for Improvement:}
\text{1. To reduce the computational resources required for the parallel denoising process in the diffusion model, consider using a more efficient diffusion model or a sampling method that reduces the number of samples required.}
\text{2. To mitigate the challenge of the non-Markovian training objective, consider using a more efficient sampling method or a different non-Markovian training objective.}
\text{3. To further evaluate the robustness of the proposed framework against adversarial attacks, consider using a more comprehensive evaluation method or a different evaluation metric.}
\text{4. To better cover the cases of incomplete state observations for state-based RL tasks, consider using a more comprehensive evaluation method or a different evaluation metric.}

$$\text{Recommendation:}
\text{Based on the experimental results and the theoretical analysis, I recommend that the authors consider using the proposed framework in real-world applications, such as autonomous driving or robotic control, where the robustness against observation perturbations is crucial. However, further evaluation is required to fully evaluate the robustness of the proposed framework against adversarial attacks and incomplete state observations.}$$

